explanation: "Posterior staphyloma is a localized outpouching of the posterior sclera, commonly seen in pathological (high) myopia.<br><br>* Concave bulging of posterior segment on ophthalmoscopy\n* Associated with axial elongation of eyeball\n* Leads to progressive visual deterioration\n<br><br><br>Pathophysiology:<br><br>* Thinning and stretching of sclera \u2192 outward bulging of posterior pole\n* Predisposes to retinal degeneration, maculopathy, and retinal detachment\n<br><br><br>Why not other options:<br><br>B. Hypermetropia<br><br>* Short eyeball \u2192 no posterior bulging\n* Retina lies anterior, not outpouched<br><br>C. Astigmatism<br><br>* Due to unequal corneal curvature\n* No posterior segment abnormality<br><br>D. Corneal ulcer<br><br>* Anterior segment pathology\n* Seen on cornea, not on fundus/ophthalmoscopy<br><br><img src=\"https://corebtr-assets-production.s3.ap-south-1.amazonaws.com/question_explanation/54d7fd2a-8156-45bf-aca6-1047c079effc.png\" alt=\"Uploaded Image\">",
