subcategory: "01-cornea-sclera",
tags: ["PYQ", "NEET PG 2022"],
text: "What is the indication of this procedure?",
options: [{"id": "A", "text": "Keratoconus", "is_correct": true}, {"id": "B", "text": "Vogt's limbal girdle", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "C", "text": "Keratoglobus", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "D", "text": "Corneal dystrophy", "is_correct": false}],
explanation: "The image shows intrastromal corneal ring segments (ICRS), which are used in the management of keratoconus.<br><br>* Keratoconus is a progressive ectatic disorder causing corneal thinning and conical protrusion, leading to irregular astigmatism and visual distortion.\n<br><br><br>Indication of the procedure:<br><br>* To flatten the cornea and improve refractive error in moderate keratoconus\n* Used when spectacles/contact lenses are not tolerated\n* Helps delay or avoid corneal transplantation\n<br><br><br>Mechanism: Ring segments inserted in corneal stroma \u2192 arc-shortening effect \u2192 central corneal flattening<br><br>Not used for:<br><br>* Vogt\u2019s limbal girdle (degenerative peripheral opacity)\n* Keratoglobus (diffuse thinning)\n* Corneal dystrophies (genetic, require different management)",
