subcategory: "01-cornea-sclera",
tags: ["PYQ", "NEET PG 2023"],
text: "What is the dye and filter used as seen in the image?",
options: [{"id": "A", "text": "Fluorescein dye - visualised under cobalt blue filter", "is_correct": true}, {"id": "B", "text": "Lissamine dye - green filter", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "C", "text": "Lissamine dye cobalt blue filter", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "D", "text": "Fluorescein dye - visualised under green filter", "is_correct": false}],
explanation: "Fluorescein staining is used to detect corneal epithelial defects and is best visualized under a cobalt blue filter.<br><br>* Fluorescein dye accumulates in areas of epithelial loss\n* Under cobalt blue light, it appears bright green (fluorescent)\n* Commonly used in corneal ulcer, abrasion, dendritic ulcers (HSV), and tear film evaluation\n<br><br><br>Clinical relevance:<br><br>*  Helps identify pattern of lesions (e.g., dendritic pattern in herpes keratitis)<br><br>\n* Used in Seidel test to detect aqueous leak\n<br><br><br>Why not others:<br><br>* Lissamine green: Stains devitalized cells, viewed in white light\n* Green filter: Not used for excitation of fluorescein",
