tags: ["PYQ", "INI-CET Nov 2023"],
text: "Which of the following accurately pairs the  diagnostic stain with the corneal condition it indicates?",
options: [{"id": "A", "text": "Cobalt blue with trypan blue for corneal ulcer", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "B", "text": "Cobalt green with Rose Bengal stain for corneal opacity", "is_correct": false}, {"id": "C", "text": "Cobalt blue with fluorescein stain for corneal ulcer", "is_correct": true}, {"id": "D", "text": "Cobalt blue with lissamine green for corneal abrasion", "is_correct": false}],
explanation: "Fluorescein staining viewed under cobalt blue light is the standard method to detect corneal epithelial defects, such as corneal ulcers and abrasions.<br><br>* Fluorescein dye stains areas where corneal epithelium is absent\n* Under cobalt blue light, these areas appear bright green\n<br><br><br>Clinical applications:<br><br>* Corneal ulcer\n* Corneal abrasion\n* Dendritic ulcers (herpes simplex)\n* Detection of foreign body tracks\n<br><br><br>Why other options are incorrect:<br><br>* Trypan blue: Used in cataract surgery (capsule staining), not cornea\n* Rose Bengal / Lissamine green: Stain devitalized or damaged epithelial cells, mainly used in dry eye, not primary for ulcers\n* Cobalt green light: Not the standard filter (cobalt blue is used)",
